There is a common misconception that using a cell phone at a gas station can ignite fumes due to electromagnetic radiation from the phone igniting gasoline vapors. However, scientific research and safety investigations have largely debunked this myth, showing that cell phone radiation is not enough to ignite gasoline vapors under normal circumstances.

The warnings against using cell phones at gas stations stem more from precautionary principles and the theoretical possibility (however minute) rather than direct, conclusive evidence that cell phones have caused fires or explosions at gas stations. The real concerns involve static electricity, particularly when individuals re-enter their vehicles while refueling, which can generate static discharge capable of igniting gasoline vapors.

